fix(notifications): add apikey header to all send-notification calls

Notifications stopped firing for the coach roughly 12 days ago. The
table was getting check-in-due rows from pg_cron and new-message
rows when the COACH messaged a CLIENT, but client->coach events
(message sent, workout completed, review ready) produced nothing.

Theory of the crime
- Direct probe of the Edge Function with no headers: 401 Unauthorized
  from the gateway. So verify_jwt is enforced at the platform level.
- The seven raw fetch() callers send Authorization: Bearer
  ${session.access_token} but NOT apikey. Supabase Edge Functions
  with verify_jwt require both at the gateway.
- supabase.functions.invoke() helpers send both automatically, which
  is why a few call paths kept working (community fan-out, etc).
- Result: every raw fetch quietly failed with 401, and the
  .catch(() => {}) on each call ate the error.

Fix
- Add 'apikey': process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY! to every
  raw fetch to /functions/v1/send-notification. Seven files touched.
- Add supabase/config.toml pinning verify_jwt for each function so
  the next CLI deploy doesn't drift from intent.

Verified
- Direct DB INSERT to notifications still works (test row from the
  bell came through).
- TypeScript compile clean across all changes.

Files
- src/app/dashboard/client/workout/[sessionId]/page.tsx
- src/app/dashboard/coach/messages/page.tsx
- src/app/dashboard/coach/nutrition/page.tsx
- src/app/dashboard/coach/outreach/page.tsx
- src/app/dashboard/coach/reviews/page.tsx
- src/app/dashboard/coach/workouts/page.tsx
- src/components/messaging/RichMessageThread.tsx
- supabase/config.toml (new)